Thus farre Christian
Reader, for thy sake I haue diued into the world, and all worldly things; if I haue said any thing in this ensuing discourse, which may yeeld thee any profit, giue God the glorie, and me thy friendly censure, and helpe I • uate me orationib •• vestris, vt s • mper possim loqui, quae op • rt • t & opere i • plere quae loqui. Bernard. in Cant.
me with thy prayers, that I may speake those things I ought, and practice my selfe what I speake. But if in any place I haue erred, then I pray correct it gently, or passe it ouer with silence; or in a friendly manner admonish me thereof, and then I haue of thee as much as I desire;
and then I shall be encouraged to set Pen to Paper againe, and publish another Treatise vpon the Parable of the Vncleane Spirit recorded by the Euangelist, Matth. 12. 43. Luke 11. 24. in which if God grant life, and opportunitie I will shew;
